(Dex has obtained a personal trainer.)

1067
00:43:00,900 --> 00:43:03,470
This will increase the workout efficiency.

1068
00:43:04,610 --> 00:43:07,310
(While Dex is fired up to work out among the brothers,)

1069
00:43:07,940 --> 00:43:11,610
(the raindrops have faded away.)

1070
00:43:12,380 --> 00:43:14,419
(Now, the clear sky is here.)

1071
00:43:14,420 --> 00:43:15,450
Gosh.

1072
00:43:16,550 --> 00:43:17,689
I want to take a photo.

1073
00:43:17,690 --> 00:43:18,690
(And an unexpected guest has come to visit the sibilings.)

1074
00:43:19,550 --> 00:43:21,120
My goodness.

1075
00:43:21,390 --> 00:43:22,420
How does it look?

1076
00:43:22,790 --> 00:43:24,289
- Gosh. - Isn't it crazy?

1077
00:43:24,290 --> 00:43:25,360
It's a real rainbow.

1078
00:43:26,090 --> 00:43:28,459
- It's a matter of course. - Hye Yoon, it's a rainbow. Look.

1079
00:43:28,460 --> 00:43:29,529
(A real rainbow has appeared.)

1080
00:43:29,530 --> 00:43:31,500
- It's really pretty. - It's so pretty.

1081
00:43:32,300 --> 00:43:33,799
How can it be so vivid?

1082
00:43:33,800 --> 00:43:35,940
(A gift from the ever-changing weather)

1083
00:43:36,540 --> 00:43:38,070
Hey. Goodness.

1084
00:43:38,840 --> 00:43:40,139
(With Jun Myun's encouragement,)

1085
00:43:40,140 --> 00:43:41,340
Gosh. Right now,

1086
00:43:42,310 --> 00:43:43,310
you look so pretty.

1087
00:43:43,311 --> 00:43:44,510
(she's in an adorable Maltese mode.)

1088
00:43:45,680 --> 00:43:47,620
(The show's bright female lead)

1089
00:43:48,050 --> 00:43:50,789
It's been years since I saw a rainbow like that.

1090
00:43:50,790 --> 00:43:51,790
Seriously.

1091
00:43:52,020 --> 00:43:53,649
(We have to capture this moment.)

1092
00:43:53,650 --> 00:43:56,460
But the duck is staring at me.

1093
00:43:57,660 --> 00:44:00,060
It's overwhelming. What should I do with it?

1094
00:44:00,430 --> 00:44:01,860
(Peeking out)

1095
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:03,030
Where's this rainbow?

1096
00:44:03,560 --> 00:44:04,999
- The rainbow is... - Jung Ah, you have to see it.

1097
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:07,029
- Jung Ah, wear those shoes. - Come and see.

1098
00:44:07,030 --> 00:44:08,040
Come here.

1099
00:44:08,870 --> 00:44:10,539
You can't see a rainbow like this in Korea.

1100
00:44:10,540 --> 00:44:11,540
- Where is it? - Over there.

1101
00:44:12,070 --> 00:44:13,740
There. It's straight ahead of us.

1102
00:44:13,910 --> 00:44:15,279
Right. I see it.

1103
00:44:15,280 --> 00:44:16,379
- Jung Ah. - Yes.

1104
00:44:16,380 --> 00:44:18,110
You sound cynical. Stand over here.

1105
00:44:18,550 --> 00:44:21,319
- She's not interested. - Let me take a photo. Come on.

1106
00:44:21,320 --> 00:44:22,379
She's not interested at all.

1107
00:44:22,380 --> 00:44:24,350
I should take a photo of you in front of the rainbow.

1108
00:44:25,320 --> 00:44:26,819
I'm wearing a rainbow shirt.

1109
00:44:26,820 --> 00:44:29,159
- That's true. - Will you stand right there?

1110
00:44:29,160 --> 00:44:30,490
You look pretty. Okay.

1111
00:44:31,130 --> 00:44:32,190
I'm done.

1112
00:44:32,690 --> 00:44:33,690
Good job.

1113
00:44:35,760 --> 00:44:38,269
(Meanwhile, Dex with a new personal trainer)

1114
00:44:38,270 --> 00:44:40,369
Do you come here every day at 2pm?

1115
00:44:40,370 --> 00:44:43,040
(He made new friends.)

1116
00:44:43,570 --> 00:44:46,270
(Student 1: Senior disciple, Personal trainer)

1117
00:44:46,640 --> 00:44:47,879
I see. Okay.

1118
00:44:47,880 --> 00:44:49,510
(Student 2: Junior disciple)

1119
00:44:50,340 --> 00:44:53,280
- Okay, my friend. It's 68kg, right? - Come.

1120
00:44:53,510 --> 00:44:55,819
"Come?" Okay. Ten.

1121
00:44:55,820 --> 00:44:57,390
(All of a sudden,)

1122
00:44:57,990 --> 00:44:59,089
Okay.

1123
00:44:59,090 --> 00:45:00,759
(the back-muscle battle between the disciples is on.)

1124
00:45:00,760 --> 00:45:02,619
(Warning: He is super excited.)

1125
00:45:02,620 --> 00:45:03,689
Ten?

1126
00:45:03,690 --> 00:45:06,660
(His 10-year experience in working out is at stake.)

1127
00:45:06,730 --> 00:45:07,730
Okay.

1128
00:45:07,731 --> 00:45:09,460
(This match matters to Dex only.)

1129
00:45:09,860 --> 00:45:12,900
(The mission is 20 reps of 68kg lat pulldown.)

1130
00:45:13,470 --> 00:45:16,540
(The senior disciple calmly works on his reps.)

1131
00:45:16,940 --> 00:45:19,940
(Focused)

1132
00:45:20,610 --> 00:45:22,440
(While all you can hear is heavy panting,)

1133
00:45:24,380 --> 00:45:25,849
(the senior disciple gives up.)

1134
00:45:25,850 --> 00:45:26,879
(Look at him.)

1135
00:45:26,880 --> 00:45:27,920
Really?

1136
00:45:27,950 --> 00:45:30,020
(I still have a long way to go.)

1137
00:45:40,190 --> 00:45:41,600
(Dex wins.)

1138
00:45:42,230 --> 00:45:45,000
(The gym-goer in his 10th year regains his honor.)

1139
00:45:45,600 --> 00:45:47,370
(The personal trainer respects him too.)

1140
00:45:47,670 --> 00:45:48,869
He must be more muscular than me without the clothes.

1141
00:45:48,870 --> 00:45:49,970
No.

1142
00:45:50,340 --> 00:45:52,340
Maybe you and I look the same.

1143
00:45:52,710 --> 00:45:53,970
- No. - You have a good body.

1144
00:45:54,740 --> 00:45:56,810
He's a bigger size. You're a medium. I'm a small.

1145
00:45:58,450 --> 00:46:02,620
(While the guys are talking about muscles,)

1146
00:46:05,220 --> 00:46:06,889
An OG is here.

1147
00:46:06,890 --> 00:46:08,860
(an extra-large size is here.)

1148
00:46:11,560 --> 00:46:15,200
(The final boss starts with 100kg.)

1149
00:46:16,860 --> 00:46:18,129
Gosh. He's intimidating me.

1150
00:46:18,130 --> 00:46:19,870
(A lat pulldown with 100kg)

1151
00:46:20,570 --> 00:46:22,899
(A hush falls over the gym.)

1152
00:46:22,900 --> 00:46:24,110
It's quiet all of a sudden.

1153
00:46:24,710 --> 00:46:26,370
Isn't it hilarious that everyone went silent?

1154
00:46:28,240 --> 00:46:29,439
The real deal is here,

1155
00:46:29,440 --> 00:46:31,150
so everyone is humbled.

1156
00:46:32,210 --> 00:46:33,809
(The lesson of the day)

1157
00:46:33,810 --> 00:46:36,880
The world is big, and there are so many strong people.

1158
00:46:37,250 --> 00:46:39,789
So many people are stronger than me here at this gym only.

1159
00:46:39,790 --> 00:46:41,590
(He finishes his workout with a sad lesson.)

1160
00:46:42,420 --> 00:46:43,989
("We Were in Love" by LYn)

1161
00:46:43,990 --> 00:46:45,530
(The sisters are relaxing, listening to Jung Ah's playlist.)

1162
00:46:46,190 --> 00:46:48,399
(You said all you wanted was me)

1163
00:46:48,400 --> 00:46:49,530
(Glancing)

1164
00:46:50,560 --> 00:46:53,230
(Is she grooving all of a sudden?)

1165
00:46:53,670 --> 00:46:55,270
(Dancing)

1166
00:46:55,370 --> 00:46:57,610
(A dance performance is held in the room in front of hers.)

1167
00:46:58,810 --> 00:47:00,339
(A concernt in the room just for Jung Ah)

1168
00:47:00,340 --> 00:47:02,880
(Laughing)

1169
00:47:03,840 --> 00:47:06,480
(The much-anticipated highlight)

1170
00:47:07,750 --> 00:47:08,820
Does it sound okay?

1171
00:47:09,650 --> 00:47:11,990
(A perfect harmony)

1172
00:47:13,350 --> 00:47:14,659
(While the bandana sisters are busy performing a duet song...)

1173
00:47:14,660 --> 00:47:16,389
I'll do it.

1174
00:47:16,390 --> 00:47:18,629
(Driving)

1175
00:47:18,630 --> 00:47:20,930
(Dex arrives.)

1176
00:47:22,860 --> 00:47:24,300
- Delivery. - For goodness' sake.

1177
00:47:25,100 --> 00:47:26,569
- Did you work out a lot? - Yes.

1178
00:47:26,570 --> 00:47:27,839
- How was the facility? - What?

1179
00:47:27,840 --> 00:47:29,799
- How was the facility? - It was better than I expected.

1180
00:47:29,800 --> 00:47:30,969
It was beyond expectation.

1181
00:47:30,970 --> 00:47:32,670
I made some friends too.

1182
00:47:33,770 --> 00:47:35,939
I beat the Chinese buddy.

1183
00:47:35,940 --> 00:47:36,940
(Bragging about beating a friend)

1184
00:47:37,080 --> 00:47:39,909
- With... - With the number of kilograms.

1185
00:47:39,910 --> 00:47:41,650
- With weight? - With weight.

1186
00:47:42,580 --> 00:47:45,020
The fact that we stayed home like this.

1187
00:47:45,320 --> 00:47:46,389
And Jin Yong went to work out.

1188
00:47:46,390 --> 00:47:48,090
It does feel like a family, doesn't it?

1189
00:47:48,160 --> 00:47:50,319
- We did our own stuff. - He said, "I'll be back."

1190
00:47:50,320 --> 00:47:52,530
- We did what we needed to do. - Yes. We did our own stuff.

1191
00:47:53,030 --> 00:47:54,599
- I'll take a shower. - Okay.

1192
00:47:54,600 --> 00:47:56,999
(The whole family has gathered now.)

1193
00:47:57,000 --> 00:47:58,570
- I'm back. - He's back.

1194
00:47:58,930 --> 00:48:01,540
He's back. Dex is back.

1195
00:48:02,300 --> 00:48:04,169
- What have you been doing? - We've been waiting for you.

1196
00:48:04,170 --> 00:48:06,340
- We'll get ready and cook now. - Yes. We'll go outside.

1197
00:48:07,110 --> 00:48:10,479
Today, actually...

1198
00:48:10,480 --> 00:48:12,810
We want something spicy.

1199
00:48:13,010 --> 00:48:15,820
Jun Myun will cook spicy beef radish soup.

1200
00:48:15,920 --> 00:48:17,420
We'll make kimchi too.

1201
00:48:17,520 --> 00:48:18,989
- And steam the crabs. - They're good crabs.

1202
00:48:18,990 --> 00:48:21,890
We'll steam them lightly and cook crab fried rice.

1203
00:48:22,190 --> 00:48:24,260
Why don't you two make the crab fried rice?

1204
00:48:24,360 --> 00:48:26,830
We'll try. I think we can do it.

1205
00:48:28,200 --> 00:48:29,960
(Today's main ingredient)

1206
00:48:31,100 --> 00:48:34,200
(They caught them in the mangrove forest themselves.)

1207
00:48:35,170 --> 00:48:41,480
(The Philippines' premium ingredient, alimango)

1208
00:48:41,580 --> 00:48:43,839
I'll extract the crab meat and make crab fried rice.

1209
00:48:43,840 --> 00:48:45,109
(Today's main chef, Dex)

1210
00:48:45,110 --> 00:48:46,380
You're a chef-owner.

1211
00:48:47,210 --> 00:48:48,849
- This is a collaboration. - Right.

1212
00:48:48,850 --> 00:48:50,120
(Always on standby next to the main chef)

1213
00:48:50,750 --> 00:48:53,250
(Capable assistant, Hye Yoon)

1214
00:48:53,450 --> 00:48:54,559
Here we go, Hye Yoon.

1215
00:48:54,560 --> 00:48:57,890
(Will the two of them cook the alimango dish successfully?)

1216
00:48:58,130 --> 00:49:00,059
I'm hungry. I'm starving.

1217
00:49:00,060 --> 00:49:01,129
Let's hurry.

1218
00:49:01,130 --> 00:49:02,430
(The four siblings' first cooking in the Philippines starts now.)

1219
00:49:02,530 --> 00:49:04,030
Where is a steamer?

1220
00:49:04,830 --> 00:49:06,170
I haven't seen one.

1221
00:49:06,830 --> 00:49:07,970
We need to steam them, right?

1222
00:49:08,240 --> 00:49:09,700
Why don't I steam them first?

1223
00:49:10,900 --> 00:49:12,040
Are they dead?

1224
00:49:12,310 --> 00:49:14,010
They're still conscious.

1225
00:49:14,940 --> 00:49:16,510
- Have you steamed crabs before? - Yes.

1226
00:49:17,280 --> 00:49:19,810
I do make steamed dishes at home.

1227
00:49:20,550 --> 00:49:23,149
- I use a cypress steamer. - I see.

1228
00:49:23,150 --> 00:49:24,150
You're good.

1229
00:49:24,720 --> 00:49:27,350
I know how to clean the crabs too.

1230
00:49:28,560 --> 00:49:30,319
(Should I start...)

1231
00:49:30,320 --> 00:49:32,460
(cleaning the alimango?)

1232
00:49:33,390 --> 00:49:35,600
(The main chef gets ready to operate.)

1233
00:49:36,230 --> 00:49:38,600
Gosh. I have to kill the crabs.

1234
00:49:41,240 --> 00:49:43,940
(He obtained a tool.)

1235
00:49:46,810 --> 00:49:49,210
Gosh. They're big.

1236
00:49:50,510 --> 00:49:53,250
(Cracking)

1237
00:49:54,080 --> 00:49:56,250
(With a scary sound, he takes alimango out.)

1238
00:49:57,620 --> 00:49:58,620
(Trying to attack him)

1239
00:49:58,621 --> 00:50:00,550
Gosh. It hurts, my friend.

1240
00:50:00,990 --> 00:50:03,390
Be careful. It has sharp claws.

1241
00:50:04,960 --> 00:50:08,500
(Testosterone-fueled Dex cleans it without hesitation.)

1242
00:50:09,230 --> 00:50:11,700
(Beating it completely)

1243
00:50:12,930 --> 00:50:16,240
(He removes the impurities from the crab first.)

1244
00:50:16,470 --> 00:50:18,470
I'll get rid of the parts that will smell bad.

1245
00:50:20,940 --> 00:50:23,079
(Chef Dex's tip)

1246
00:50:23,080 --> 00:50:26,179
(Drain out the blood after removing the underside and mouth...)

1247
00:50:26,180 --> 00:50:28,949
(to reduce fishy and earthy smell.)

1248
00:50:28,950 --> 00:50:32,649
Because it was in the mud, we might get mud in our mouths.

1249
00:50:32,650 --> 00:50:33,650
Exactly.

1250
00:50:34,120 --> 00:50:35,789
I have to clean them thoroughly.

1251
00:50:35,790 --> 00:50:37,759
(Cleaning them thoroughly under running water...)

1252
00:50:37,760 --> 00:50:39,390
(without leaving any mud)

1253
00:50:41,460 --> 00:50:44,730
(He skillfully prepares the first alimango.)

1254
00:50:45,200 --> 00:50:47,500
(Assistant Hye Yoon comes to help the chef.)

1255
00:50:47,700 --> 00:50:48,940
Is it alive?

1256
00:50:49,440 --> 00:50:50,999
- It must be dead. - That one's dead.

1257
00:50:51,000 --> 00:50:52,409
These ones are alive.

1258
00:50:52,410 --> 00:50:54,540
Don't touch them. You might hurt your hands.

1259
00:50:54,940 --> 00:50:56,040
Watch your hands.

1260
00:50:56,780 --> 00:50:57,780
Okay.

1261
00:50:57,781 --> 00:50:59,950
(Testosterone-fueled Dex is so kind to the younger sister.)

1262
00:51:00,450 --> 00:51:03,150
(He takes out the next alimango.)

1263
00:51:04,520 --> 00:51:06,289
(Thrashing)

1264
00:51:06,290 --> 00:51:07,350
It's strong.

1265
00:51:08,860 --> 00:51:10,159
(For attempting to escape,)

1266
00:51:10,160 --> 00:51:12,090
(it's sent to a pot jail.)

1267
00:51:12,890 --> 00:51:14,129
He's pushing it down.

1268
00:51:14,130 --> 00:51:15,660
(A miserable end of the fugitive)

1269
00:51:16,660 --> 00:51:18,300
Gosh. Look how hard it grabs.

1270
00:51:18,970 --> 00:51:20,400
It might cut my finger off.

1271
00:51:21,640 --> 00:51:24,510
(It doesn't let go of the scissors.)

1272
00:51:24,640 --> 00:51:25,740
Will you pass me the knife?

1273
00:51:26,540 --> 00:51:27,880
Did it take your scissors?

1274
00:51:28,110 --> 00:51:29,239
Here's a small one.

1275
00:51:29,240 --> 00:51:31,609
- Do you need a big one? - No. A small one is fine.

1276
00:51:31,610 --> 00:51:32,950
(He has obtained another tool.)

1277
00:51:38,650 --> 00:51:41,620
(He barely knocks it off with 2 tools, a knife and scissors.)

1278
00:51:43,060 --> 00:51:45,590
(Scary)

1279
00:51:46,190 --> 00:51:47,459
(After cleaning the alimango enthusiastically...)

1280
00:51:47,460 --> 00:51:49,729
- Jin Young, let me wash my hands. - Okay.

1281
00:51:49,730 --> 00:51:51,570
Gosh. Is this all right?

1282
00:51:52,070 --> 00:51:54,029
It's not clogged, is it?

1283
00:51:54,030 --> 00:51:55,700
It got clogged right away.

1284
00:51:56,100 --> 00:51:57,100
What do we do?

1285
00:51:57,200 --> 00:51:58,840
The water goes down after a while.

1286
00:51:59,470 --> 00:52:01,280
- Should I unclog it? - What?

1287
00:52:03,480 --> 00:52:04,850
(Will it work?)

1288
00:52:05,050 --> 00:52:06,080
As for this one...

1289
00:52:07,710 --> 00:52:09,150
There must be something to lift it up.

1290
00:52:10,120 --> 00:52:12,850
(For some reason, she looks very professional.)

1291
00:52:13,250 --> 00:52:15,360
Right.

1292
00:52:18,690 --> 00:52:21,160
(The sink is unclogged with a few moves by her.)

1293
00:52:21,300 --> 00:52:22,329
Nice. You unclogged it.

1294
00:52:22,330 --> 00:52:26,099
Yes. I lived by myself before.

1295
00:52:26,100 --> 00:52:27,700
(The vibe from living alone)

1296
00:52:27,900 --> 00:52:29,839
- You're good. - Of course.

1297
00:52:29,840 --> 00:52:30,840
(She's on top of everything.)

1298
00:52:30,841 --> 00:52:33,270
When I hand it to you after killing it,

1299
00:52:33,370 --> 00:52:35,880
- Yes. - check for any mud in it.

1300
00:52:36,410 --> 00:52:38,379
Wash it with water.

1301
00:52:38,380 --> 00:52:40,509
(She helps him clean the crabs without a problem.)

1302
00:52:40,510 --> 00:52:41,520
You're doing great.

1303
00:52:41,820 --> 00:52:43,780
(Thanks to the skillful assistant Hye Yoon,)

1304
00:52:44,520 --> 00:52:45,989
Mission complete.

1305
00:52:45,990 --> 00:52:48,090
(the alimangos are cleaned and prepped.)

1306
00:52:48,460 --> 00:52:50,690
(What is the skillful assistant's next job?)

1307
00:52:51,330 --> 00:52:53,559
Sort them out, Hye Yoon.

1308
00:52:53,560 --> 00:52:55,100
- Okay. - Pick and throw them away.

1309
00:52:55,560 --> 00:52:57,870
- Pick out the bad cabbage. - Okay.

1310
00:52:58,500 --> 00:53:00,670
Take out the damaged leaves like this one.

1311
00:53:00,870 --> 00:53:02,469
- Damaged like this? - Yes.

1312
00:53:02,470 --> 00:53:03,500
(Checking if there are damaged leaves)

1313
00:53:04,100 --> 00:53:05,109
This one is a little...

1314
00:53:05,110 --> 00:53:07,470
(Totally focused as if she's looking into a microscope)

1315
00:53:08,210 --> 00:53:12,050
(After preparing the napa cabbage for a while...)

1316
00:53:13,250 --> 00:53:15,150
- There's a lot. - I know.

1317
00:53:15,680 --> 00:53:17,890
When I brine these,

1318
00:53:18,550 --> 00:53:20,620
- They'll shrink. - they'll shrink a lot.

1319
00:53:21,050 --> 00:53:23,159
We have to eat kimchi for days.

1320
00:53:23,160 --> 00:53:24,360
(It's the amount for the whole vacation.)

1321
00:53:24,460 --> 00:53:26,190
We need to wash the napa cabbage inside.

1322
00:53:27,330 --> 00:53:28,560
Is there a big strainer?

1323
00:53:29,300 --> 00:53:31,700
- I found this one. - That won't work. Is it in there?

1324
00:53:33,170 --> 00:53:34,500
Gosh. They look good.

1325
00:53:34,740 --> 00:53:36,699
(The assistant doesn't understand how generous Jung Ah is.)

1326
00:53:36,700 --> 00:53:37,800
What about this one, Jung Ah?

1327
00:53:38,210 --> 00:53:39,610
That looks good.

1328
00:53:40,340 --> 00:53:41,810
- Thank you. - No problem.

1329
00:53:42,980 --> 00:53:46,450
(After washing it under running water,)

1330
00:53:48,580 --> 00:53:50,519
We need to salt the napa cabbage.

1331
00:53:50,520 --> 00:53:53,090
(salt the napa cabbage with coarse salt until it wilts.)

1332
00:53:53,950 --> 00:53:56,260
(At one corner of the kitchen...)

1333
00:53:59,273 --> 00:54:01,573
(At one corner of the kitchen,)

1334
00:54:04,876 --> 00:54:08,416
(Jun Myun crouches to clean the radish.)

1335
00:54:13,416 --> 00:54:16,416
(She chops the radish into big chunks.)

1336
00:54:17,256 --> 00:54:18,325
Gosh.

1337
00:54:18,326 --> 00:54:20,386
(Tasting it like always)

1338
00:54:20,626 --> 00:54:22,096
Okay. Now, I put...

1339
00:54:23,196 --> 00:54:25,696
Jung Ah, do I marinate it with soup soy sauce?

1340
00:54:25,996 --> 00:54:27,395
- Yes, with soup soy sauce. - Soup soy sauce?

1341
00:54:27,396 --> 00:54:28,396
Yes.

1342
00:54:28,397 --> 00:54:29,896
(Is Jun Myun asking Jung Ah for the recipe?)

1343
00:54:31,336 --> 00:54:33,265
No. I'll teach you.

1344
00:54:33,266 --> 00:54:36,536
Chop the radish and marinate it in soup soy sauce for a while.

1345
00:54:36,936 --> 00:54:38,346
Drain the blood out of the beef.

1346
00:54:38,446 --> 00:54:40,306
- Add minced garlic. - Add a bit of minced garlic.

1347
00:54:40,406 --> 00:54:43,376
Instead of using oil, stir-fry the meat with cooking wine.

1348
00:54:43,746 --> 00:54:47,016
I see. You use cooking wine to stir-fry the beef.

1349
00:54:47,116 --> 00:54:48,255
- Don't put any oil in. - No oil.

1350
00:54:48,256 --> 00:54:49,985
- For spicy beef radish soup. - It'll taste cleaner.

1351
00:54:49,986 --> 00:54:51,485
Yes. It will taste very clean and light.

1352
00:54:51,486 --> 00:54:52,526
(She learned the recipe perfectly.)

1353
00:54:53,156 --> 00:54:55,126
(Now, it's time to cook.)

1354
00:54:55,226 --> 00:54:57,055
(Jung Ah's recipe for spicy beef radish soup)

1355
00:54:57,056 --> 00:54:58,996
(1. Marinating radish in soup soy sauce)

1356
00:54:59,766 --> 00:55:03,466
(Next, it's time to drain blood from the beef.)

1357
00:55:04,066 --> 00:55:05,565
I rubbed the blood off.

1358
00:55:05,566 --> 00:55:07,636
(2. Remove the blood from the beef completely.)

1359
00:55:09,206 --> 00:55:11,946
(Adding lots of minced garlic to remove foul odor)

1360
00:55:12,406 --> 00:55:14,405
(3. Add minced garlic to the beef.)

1361
00:55:14,406 --> 00:55:16,676
(4. Stir-fry the beef with cooking wine, not oil.)

1362
00:55:16,776 --> 00:55:18,145
Does the gas stove work now?

1363
00:55:18,146 --> 00:55:20,646
(It's time to stir-fry the beef with cooking wine now.)

1364
00:55:22,716 --> 00:55:26,756
(Is she turning on the gas for the pot of radish?)

1365
00:55:27,226 --> 00:55:30,226
(She stir-fries the radish confidently.)

1366
00:55:31,156 --> 00:55:33,326
I marinated it in soy sauce. Now...

1367
00:55:33,566 --> 00:55:34,795
You need to stir-fry the beef first.

1368
00:55:34,796 --> 00:55:37,835
You can just add the marinated radish later on.

1369
00:55:37,836 --> 00:55:39,236
You need to stir-fry the beef first.

1370
00:55:39,306 --> 00:55:41,436
- Is that so? - Yes.

1371
00:55:42,676 --> 00:55:43,676
What should I do with it?

1372
00:55:43,677 --> 00:55:45,505
Did you add just a little bit of the soy sauce?

1373
00:55:45,506 --> 00:55:47,906
- Yes. - You should've added much more.

1374
00:55:48,076 --> 00:55:49,816
Stir-fry the beef in another pot.

1375
00:55:50,119 --> 00:55:51,619
No, I'll redo it.

1376
00:55:51,789 --> 00:55:54,619
I think... Can I do what I think?

1377
00:55:57,119 --> 00:55:59,089
- Sure, do what you like. - I mean...

1378
00:55:59,729 --> 00:56:01,798
I think it'll work this way...

1379
00:56:01,799 --> 00:56:03,358
- or that way. - Okay.

1380
00:56:03,359 --> 00:56:05,169
Sure, do what you like.

1381
00:56:06,429 --> 00:56:09,139
(What will become of spicy beef radish soup?)

1382
00:56:09,669 --> 00:56:11,638
(Spicy beef radish soup...)

1383
00:56:11,639 --> 00:56:12,968
(I'll revive you, no matter what.)

1384
00:56:12,969 --> 00:56:14,139
(Lips tightened in resolution)

1385
00:56:17,679 --> 00:56:20,149
(She adds two spoonfuls of chili powder to make it spicy.)

1386
00:56:21,149 --> 00:56:23,649
(Beef enters.)

1387
00:56:24,049 --> 00:56:26,048
They say add cooking wine when stir-frying it...

1388
00:56:26,049 --> 00:56:27,519
for the clean taste.

1389
00:56:27,889 --> 00:56:30,318
I'll make it spicy and clean.

1390
00:56:30,319 --> 00:56:32,429
(The kick to having clean-tasting soup)

1391
00:56:35,399 --> 00:56:36,628
(Surprised)

1392
00:56:36,629 --> 00:56:38,729
I'll add water and boil it now.

1393
00:56:39,269 --> 00:56:40,468
It smells good.

1394
00:56:40,469 --> 00:56:42,298
- It smells delicious, right? - Yes.

1395
00:56:42,299 --> 00:56:43,438
- It'll be spicy. - Yes.

1396
00:56:43,439 --> 00:56:46,639
(The scent of Korea fills the air of Bohol.)

1397
00:56:48,279 --> 00:56:51,679
(When the beef is almost cooked, add some water.)

1398
00:56:54,849 --> 00:56:56,479
Let's make it pretty spicy.

1399
00:56:57,449 --> 00:56:58,518
And refreshing.

1400
00:56:58,519 --> 00:57:00,119
(Adding green onions to make it refreshing)

1401
00:57:00,589 --> 00:57:03,158
(Soup soy sauce, tuna sauce, seasoned salt, pepper)

1402
00:57:03,159 --> 00:57:05,189
(Season it using 4 types of seasonings.)

1403
00:57:06,589 --> 00:57:07,788
It needs to cook.

1404
00:57:07,789 --> 00:57:09,829
(Let it boil for a bit.)

1405
00:57:10,129 --> 00:57:11,628
- I'll do it my way. - Okay.

1406
00:57:11,629 --> 00:57:13,399
- I'll make it spicy. - Okay.

1407
00:57:14,199 --> 00:57:16,468
(Will she be able to satisfy Chef Yum?)

1408
00:57:16,469 --> 00:57:17,698
What should I do with this?

1409
00:57:17,699 --> 00:57:19,909
- Is it all salted? - It's done, right?

1410
00:57:20,469 --> 00:57:22,278
- Hye Yoon, can you check... - Yes.

1411
00:57:22,279 --> 00:57:24,538
- if the rice is ready? - Okay.

1412
00:57:24,539 --> 00:57:27,578
If it is, can you mix it with a rice scoop?

1413
00:57:27,579 --> 00:57:28,579
Okay, will do.

1414
00:57:28,779 --> 00:57:30,419
I need it to make kimchi.

1415
00:57:31,319 --> 00:57:32,349
Rice.

1416
00:57:35,219 --> 00:57:36,918
"Check if the rice is ready."

1417
00:57:36,919 --> 00:57:39,889
"If it is, can you mix it..."

1418
00:57:40,959 --> 00:57:42,499
"with a rice scoop?"

1419
00:57:42,899 --> 00:57:44,259
To check if the rice is ready,

1420
00:57:44,659 --> 00:57:45,868
I should taste a bit of it.

1421
00:57:45,869 --> 00:57:47,599
(How to check if the rice is ready? By tasting it.)

1422
00:57:50,399 --> 00:57:51,569
Is this how you eat it?

1423
00:57:55,679 --> 00:57:56,878
(Satisfied)

1424
00:57:56,879 --> 00:57:57,939
It's firm.

1425
00:57:59,209 --> 00:58:00,608
Mix it.

1426
00:58:00,609 --> 00:58:02,279
(The smart assistant executes the commands one by one.)

1427
00:58:03,919 --> 00:58:07,819
If we have this with soup or jjigae...

1428
00:58:08,919 --> 00:58:09,988
That'll be amazing.

1429
00:58:09,989 --> 00:58:11,189
(Just imagining it makes her happy.)

1430
00:58:11,419 --> 00:58:12,829
This should be enough, right?

1431
00:58:13,659 --> 00:58:15,299
Exactly. My goodness.

1432
00:58:15,659 --> 00:58:16,859
Is she narrating?

1433
00:58:17,129 --> 00:58:20,428
I mixed it so many times. This should be enough, right?

1434
00:58:20,429 --> 00:58:21,739
(She's talking to herself.)

1435
00:58:22,199 --> 00:58:24,439
I'll report to Jung Ah.

1436
00:58:25,469 --> 00:58:26,968
Jung Ah, I finished mixing it.

1437
00:58:26,969 --> 00:58:28,239
My goodness.

1438
00:58:28,909 --> 00:58:30,109
The rice is very firm.

1439
00:58:30,579 --> 00:58:32,649
- It's so delicious. - I purposely made it firm.

1440
00:58:34,079 --> 00:58:37,018
(We'll reveal Chef Yum's kimchi recipe.)

1441
00:58:37,019 --> 00:58:39,489
(Overseas version)

1442
00:58:40,349 --> 00:58:41,889
You're not making glutinous rice paste, right?

1443
00:58:42,089 --> 00:58:43,888
No. I'll just blend them with rice.

1444
00:58:43,889 --> 00:58:45,329
(I'll blend the ingredients with rice.)

1445
00:58:47,329 --> 00:58:49,829
(She replaces the missing ingredient with cooled rice.)

1446
00:58:50,859 --> 00:58:54,399
(One whole sweet onion)

1447
00:58:54,939 --> 00:58:57,539
(Adding apples to enhance the sweetness)

1448
00:58:57,869 --> 00:58:59,709
(Fermented shrimp)

1449
00:59:00,069 --> 00:59:02,209
(Plum extract)

1450
00:59:02,809 --> 00:59:06,379
(Put the cooled down rice straight into the blender.)

1451
00:59:06,809 --> 00:59:08,248
(Chef Yum's tip: You can replace glutinous rice paste with rice,)

1452
00:59:08,249 --> 00:59:09,778
(which both has the effect of the kimchi sauce...)

1453
00:59:09,779 --> 00:59:11,449
(being absorbed well by napa cabbage.)

1454
00:59:12,789 --> 00:59:16,189
(Put all the ingredients in and blend them finely.)

1455
00:59:18,529 --> 00:59:23,859
(Finely-ground kimchi sauce base)

1456
00:59:24,799 --> 00:59:27,398
(Adding a generous amount of Korean flavor)

1457
00:59:27,399 --> 00:59:29,999
(Minced garlic and chili powder)

1458
00:59:30,569 --> 00:59:33,109
(Add the refreshing taste with anchovy fish sauce.)

1459
00:59:33,809 --> 00:59:36,079
(Add tuna sauce for enhanced umami.)

1460
00:59:36,739 --> 00:59:38,949
(Mix them together.)

1461
00:59:39,309 --> 00:59:40,309
How is it?

1462
00:59:40,310 --> 00:59:42,749
(How does the sauce taste?)

1463
00:59:43,649 --> 00:59:44,719
It's spicy.

1464
00:59:46,049 --> 00:59:47,548
The chili powder is very coarse.

1465
00:59:47,549 --> 00:59:48,719
(The perfect spicy Korean flavor)

1466
00:59:48,919 --> 00:59:50,388
- It's done. - It's done?

1467
00:59:50,389 --> 00:59:53,859
(It's time to mix them nicely.)

1468
00:59:53,989 --> 00:59:55,228
Some spring onions.

1469
00:59:55,229 --> 00:59:56,399
(Add sharp spring onions.)

1470
00:59:57,599 --> 01:00:01,939
(She mixes it with her generous hand.)

1471
01:00:03,039 --> 01:00:04,168
Two bowls of rice.

1472
01:00:04,169 --> 01:00:05,709
You can have geotjeori with rice as you make it.

1473
01:00:06,739 --> 01:00:08,279
Would you like to try? Have you tried it?

1474
01:00:08,739 --> 01:00:10,178
- Let me put one in your mouth. - Please.

1475
01:00:10,179 --> 01:00:14,379
(How does kimchi made in the Philippines taste?)

1476
01:00:15,579 --> 01:00:18,649
(Expressing the taste with her whole body)

1477
01:00:18,789 --> 01:00:20,249
It tastes ripe, right?

1478
01:00:20,519 --> 01:00:22,059
- Yes. It's tasty. - The napa cabbage is...

1479
01:00:23,689 --> 01:00:27,189
(She moves the generous amount of kimchi into a kimchi container.)

1480
01:00:28,129 --> 01:00:29,829
(Not leaving out any sauce)

1481
01:00:30,659 --> 01:00:32,298
We'll rely on this for the next few days.

1482
01:00:32,299 --> 01:00:33,698
(It'll take care of the siblings' meals...)

1483
01:00:33,699 --> 01:00:35,399
(during the vacation.)

1484
01:00:35,769 --> 01:00:37,369
Hye Yoon, let us get started.

1485
01:00:37,999 --> 01:00:39,369
- The water is boiling. - Okay.

1486
01:00:39,939 --> 01:00:41,069
This is for the steam?

1487
01:00:41,269 --> 01:00:43,238
Add half a bottle of rice wine...

1488
01:00:43,239 --> 01:00:45,708
to sanitize it.

1489
01:00:45,709 --> 01:00:47,079
(Pouring rice wine into boiling water)

1490
01:00:47,679 --> 01:00:49,078
The rice wine smells nice.

1491
01:00:49,079 --> 01:00:50,449
(Add rice wine when steaming crabs to remove the fishy smell.)

1492
01:00:51,049 --> 01:00:53,648
(Cleanly-washed alimangos...)

1493
01:00:53,649 --> 01:00:57,119
(are placed in the steamer.)

1494
01:00:57,559 --> 01:00:59,088
(While alimangos are being steamed)

1495
01:00:59,089 --> 01:01:02,129
I'll cut the ingredients for fried rice.

1496
01:01:02,629 --> 01:01:05,329
Use this to make green onion oil for fried rice.

1497
01:01:06,729 --> 01:01:08,939
Just cut simply and put them in here so I can blend them.

1498
01:01:10,939 --> 01:01:13,839
(Blend them finely using a blender.)

1499
01:01:15,179 --> 01:01:17,639
(Lightly beat the eggs too.)

1500
01:01:17,939 --> 01:01:19,148
Fry the rice now.

1501
01:01:19,149 --> 01:01:21,449
(The ingredients for crab fried rice are ready too!)

1502
01:01:21,919 --> 01:01:23,119
Do you need anything else?

1503
01:01:23,919 --> 01:01:25,689
(Let me think.)

1504
01:01:25,919 --> 01:01:28,249
What about honey? Syrup?

1505
01:01:28,359 --> 01:01:30,589
Why'd you add syrup to fried rice?

1506
01:01:30,989 --> 01:01:32,788
I actually can't tell if this is honey...

1507
01:01:32,789 --> 01:01:34,459
or that cinnamon thing.

1508
01:01:34,829 --> 01:01:35,899
What about MSG?

1509
01:01:36,129 --> 01:01:37,199
(You're funny.)

1510
01:01:37,399 --> 01:01:39,398
I only make use of the natural taste.

1511
01:01:39,399 --> 01:01:40,698
- Okay. - I don't use condiments.

1512
01:01:40,699 --> 01:01:41,699
Okay.

1513
01:01:42,739 --> 01:01:44,599
Let's prepare some.

1514
01:01:45,339 --> 01:01:46,509
- MSG? - Yes.

1515
01:01:46,669 --> 01:01:49,008
- Place it close to me. - Okay.

1516
01:01:49,009 --> 01:01:50,738
- MSG. - But don't let others see it.

1517
01:01:50,739 --> 01:01:52,479
- Okay. - Cover it with something else.

1518
01:01:52,609 --> 01:01:54,408
I got you. Like this, so it doesn't show.

1519
01:01:54,409 --> 01:01:56,119
- That's it. - Okay.

1520
01:01:56,479 --> 01:01:58,418
The new part-timer must be pretty good.

1521
01:01:58,419 --> 01:01:59,419
Yes.

1522
01:01:59,420 --> 01:02:01,619
- She... - We hired a clever one.

1523
01:02:02,159 --> 01:02:03,418
She's competent.

1524
01:02:03,419 --> 01:02:05,359
She looks clever.

1525
01:02:05,889 --> 01:02:07,559
I hear she's academically bright too.

1526
01:02:08,399 --> 01:02:10,459
Are you the one who went to Seoul National University?

1527
01:02:10,829 --> 01:02:12,199
(She doesn't know what to do.)

1528
01:02:12,569 --> 01:02:14,599
- Respond to her. - The university's medical school.

1529
01:02:14,699 --> 01:02:16,069
I heard that you study medicine in Seoul National University.

1530
01:02:16,169 --> 01:02:18,569
Yes, I guess so.

1531
01:02:18,909 --> 01:02:20,069
- My gosh. - "I guess so."

1532
01:02:20,269 --> 01:02:21,339
Did I?

1533
01:02:22,309 --> 01:02:23,339
It...

1534
01:02:23,539 --> 01:02:25,978
- Did it turn red? - Yes, the inside turned red.

1535
01:02:25,979 --> 01:02:27,679
That's amazing.

1536
01:02:28,419 --> 01:02:30,119
They're being steamed.

1537
01:02:30,949 --> 01:02:32,589
- Jung Ah, I turned on the heat. - Thanks.

1538
01:02:32,949 --> 01:02:34,449
What are you going to make?

1539
01:02:35,019 --> 01:02:37,489
The sauce to go with crabs.

1540
01:02:39,159 --> 01:02:41,899
For the sauce, butter and garlic.

1541
01:02:43,199 --> 01:02:44,729
(She cuts the butter, which will add the savory flavor.)

1542
01:02:47,529 --> 01:02:50,699
(Let it melt in the frying pan.)

1543
01:02:51,599 --> 01:02:55,009
(When the butter is somewhat melted,)

1544
01:02:57,279 --> 01:02:59,279
(add some minced garlic.)

1545
01:02:59,509 --> 01:03:03,049
You need to use low heat to stir-fry garlic gently.

1546
01:03:03,949 --> 01:03:05,918
Salt and pepper.

1547
01:03:05,919 --> 01:03:07,049
(Sprinkle salt and pepper.)

1548
01:03:07,589 --> 01:03:09,459
You're making a golden sauce.

1549
01:03:09,619 --> 01:03:10,758
That's a nice color.

1550
01:03:10,759 --> 01:03:12,289
(Jung Ah's golden butter garlic sauce)

1551
01:03:12,959 --> 01:03:15,559
(How does the golden sauce taste?)

1552
01:03:15,729 --> 01:03:16,729
(Humming)

1553
01:03:16,730 --> 01:03:18,598
- Jung Ah. - It's seasoned well.

1554
01:03:18,599 --> 01:03:20,869
(I approve.)

1555
01:03:22,139 --> 01:03:23,139
(Hissing)

1556
01:03:24,999 --> 01:03:26,009
(Slurping)

1557
01:03:28,609 --> 01:03:29,609
(Blowing)

1558
01:03:29,679 --> 01:03:31,109
Are you having a meal?

1559
01:03:34,049 --> 01:03:35,848
(What are you doing?)

1560
01:03:35,849 --> 01:03:37,548
- No, I'm tasting it. - What are you eating?

1561
01:03:37,549 --> 01:03:39,549
- What are you eating? - Radish soup.

1562
01:03:39,689 --> 01:03:41,249
You keep blowing something.

1563
01:03:41,719 --> 01:03:43,859
- In a mug? - I thought you were having a meal.

1564
01:03:45,019 --> 01:03:46,089
Jun Myun.

1565
01:03:46,729 --> 01:03:48,698
That's practically one serving.

1566
01:03:48,699 --> 01:03:50,029
I asked you to taste it.

1567
01:03:50,859 --> 01:03:53,998
I mean, I need to check if it smells gamey...

1568
01:03:53,999 --> 01:03:56,068
- among many other things. - You're checking?

1569
01:03:56,069 --> 01:03:57,199
My goodness.

1570
01:03:57,639 --> 01:03:59,169
No wonder there's so much.

1571
01:03:59,739 --> 01:04:01,438
(Embarrassed)

1572
01:04:01,439 --> 01:04:03,239
I think it's a bit bland.

1573
01:04:03,609 --> 01:04:05,149
(Another spoonful)

1574
01:04:06,109 --> 01:04:07,809
- Does it taste okay? - It's okay,

1575
01:04:08,379 --> 01:04:10,418
but I think it's a tiny bit bland.

1576
01:04:10,419 --> 01:04:11,548
It's bland?

1577
01:04:11,549 --> 01:04:13,718
(When you're not sure,)

1578
01:04:13,719 --> 01:04:16,519
(take another mouthful.)

1579
01:04:17,689 --> 01:04:21,029
(She adds some soup soy sauce to finish it...)

1580
01:04:21,559 --> 01:04:25,059
(and then starts the 2nd round of her meal.)

1581
01:04:26,599 --> 01:04:28,269
- We're not yet... - I'm tasting it.

1582
01:04:28,539 --> 01:04:30,969
Haven't you been tasting all this while?

1583
01:04:33,339 --> 01:04:35,838
I added more soy sauce because it was a bit bland.

1584
01:04:35,839 --> 01:04:36,879
I see.

1585
01:04:36,939 --> 01:04:38,678
- You're tasting it again? - Yes.

1586
01:04:38,679 --> 01:04:40,408
(It's a must to taste it after you season it.)

1587
01:04:40,409 --> 01:04:41,609
I'll try it again.

1588
01:04:42,119 --> 01:04:43,479
She scooped up another ladleful.

1589
01:04:44,449 --> 01:04:45,919
- This is her second round. - I mean...

1590
01:04:46,719 --> 01:04:49,318
- Jun Myun. - This is good for me.

1591
01:04:49,319 --> 01:04:50,389
This should do.

1592
01:04:50,919 --> 01:04:53,259
Would you like to try again? I seasoned it one last time.

1593
01:04:53,359 --> 01:04:55,428
- It's impossible to resist. - Really?

1594
01:04:55,429 --> 01:04:56,429
(It's impossible to resist.)

1595
01:04:56,559 --> 01:04:57,728
I'll give you two pieces of radish.

1596
01:04:57,729 --> 01:04:59,598
- All right. - I'm being generous.

1597
01:04:59,599 --> 01:05:00,828
(She generously gives her 2 pieces of radish.)

1598
01:05:00,829 --> 01:05:01,899
The seasoning.

1599
01:05:03,699 --> 01:05:04,939
The radish is cooked well.

1600
01:05:05,609 --> 01:05:07,809
(Looking forward to her reaction)

1601
01:05:08,009 --> 01:05:09,908
(Both humming)

1602
01:05:09,909 --> 01:05:11,079
I'm not doing this just for fun.

1603
01:05:13,509 --> 01:05:15,349
- You keep getting drawn to it. - Right?

1604
01:05:15,749 --> 01:05:17,619
I'll add a bit more pepper one last time.

1605
01:05:18,889 --> 01:05:19,919
Pepper.

1606
01:05:21,089 --> 01:05:22,359
And you'll taste it again, right?

1607
01:05:23,559 --> 01:05:24,719
The final tasting.

1608
01:05:25,829 --> 01:05:27,358
The soup is ready.

1609
01:05:27,359 --> 01:05:29,759
(Spicy beef radish soup, the final seasoned version)

1610
01:05:30,259 --> 01:05:32,099
It should already be 6pm, right?

1611
01:05:32,329 --> 01:05:35,838
Now? Yes. It's 6:30pm, Jung Ah.

1612
01:05:35,839 --> 01:05:37,098
We should eat at 7pm.

1613
01:05:37,099 --> 01:05:38,538
(Current time: 6:30pm)

1614
01:05:38,539 --> 01:05:40,008
It needs to steam for 25 minutes.

1615
01:05:40,009 --> 01:05:41,909
There's still ten more minutes to go.

1616
01:05:42,439 --> 01:05:43,679
- Ten minutes? - Yes.

1617
01:05:44,279 --> 01:05:45,979
We need to be quick.

1618
01:05:46,509 --> 01:05:47,709
I'm starting to feel rushed.

1619
01:05:48,049 --> 01:05:49,049
I'll give it a go.

1620
01:05:49,919 --> 01:05:50,949
We can do well.

1621
01:05:51,049 --> 01:05:53,488
- You guys better hurry. I'm hungry. - Okay.

1622
01:05:53,489 --> 01:05:55,619
Depending on how fast we are...

1623
01:05:55,759 --> 01:05:57,619
- That'll decide our dinnertime. - That's right.

1624
01:05:58,589 --> 01:06:01,558
(10 minutes which felt like forever pass.)

1625
01:06:01,559 --> 01:06:02,829
The alarm rang.

1626
01:06:04,299 --> 01:06:05,399
Okay, let's go.

1627
01:06:05,669 --> 01:06:07,399
- Okay. - Shall we check it out?

1628
01:06:08,099 --> 01:06:09,769
(Pausing)

1629
01:06:10,269 --> 01:06:11,369
You open it.

1630
01:06:12,209 --> 01:06:14,768
Why? Why would you hand over such a tense moment to me?

1631
01:06:14,769 --> 01:06:15,979
(Feeling very pressured)

1632
01:06:22,149 --> 01:06:24,378
(Shimmering)

1633
01:06:24,379 --> 01:06:25,549
Look at the color. That's amazing.

1634
01:06:27,549 --> 01:06:30,558
- The color is really... - It's pretty.

1635
01:06:30,559 --> 01:06:31,559
The color is amazing.

1636
01:06:31,560 --> 01:06:33,588
It's scarlet, not red.

1637
01:06:33,589 --> 01:06:35,158
I've never seen this color on crabs before.

1638
01:06:35,159 --> 01:06:36,159
(They're a lot more scarlet than Korean blue crabs.)

1639
01:06:36,160 --> 01:06:38,098
- You're going to remove the meat? - Yes.

1640
01:06:38,099 --> 01:06:39,729
- Yes. - This is the crucial part.

1641
01:06:40,069 --> 01:06:41,069
Be fast.

1642
01:06:41,769 --> 01:06:43,698
- Hye Yoon. - Yes, boss.

1643
01:06:43,699 --> 01:06:45,269
- Bring over the plate. - Okay.

1644
01:06:45,939 --> 01:06:47,269
Hurry up.

1645
01:06:47,509 --> 01:06:48,509
My goodness.

1646
01:06:48,510 --> 01:06:50,039
(Speed is of utmost importance now.)

1647
01:06:50,479 --> 01:06:52,009
- It's hot, right? - It's fine.

1648
01:06:52,079 --> 01:06:54,148
- The color... - It's so red, right?

1649
01:06:54,149 --> 01:06:55,918
(Even when looking at it again, it's such a bright color.)

1650
01:06:55,919 --> 01:06:58,819
Let's set the prettiest three aside.

1651
01:06:59,219 --> 01:07:00,289
Sure.

1652
01:07:00,319 --> 01:07:01,589
- What do you think? - That's nice.

1653
01:07:01,819 --> 01:07:03,488
This is done.

1654
01:07:03,489 --> 01:07:04,618
- Here. - Put them here.

1655
01:07:04,619 --> 01:07:05,629
Now.

1656
01:07:06,029 --> 01:07:07,188
Do we do one by one?

1657
01:07:07,189 --> 01:07:08,899
No. That's right, good job removing it.

1658
01:07:09,399 --> 01:07:11,029
It'll be better to squeeze it out using our hands.

1659
01:07:11,969 --> 01:07:12,969
Isn't it hot?

1660
01:07:14,599 --> 01:07:16,338
- It must be very hot. - Exactly.

1661
01:07:16,339 --> 01:07:20,139
(Squeezing out the meat that's filling up the shell)

1662
01:07:20,209 --> 01:07:21,209
This...

1663
01:07:22,209 --> 01:07:24,379
(Gasping)

1664
01:07:24,539 --> 01:07:26,308
- It popped out. - That's how it is.

1665
01:07:26,309 --> 01:07:27,978
Collect the meat here.

1666
01:07:27,979 --> 01:07:29,918
(Ecstatic)

1667
01:07:29,919 --> 01:07:31,819
- Taste it. - It's okay.

1668
01:07:32,649 --> 01:07:33,649
I held myself back.

1669
01:07:35,149 --> 01:07:36,158
I should hold myself back for this.

1670
01:07:36,159 --> 01:07:38,419
(Suppressing the urge to eat it, they pile up the meat.)

1671
01:07:39,259 --> 01:07:40,558
(And the highlight of alimango)

1672
01:07:40,559 --> 01:07:42,628
You're good.

1673
01:07:42,629 --> 01:07:43,728
Like this.

1674
01:07:43,729 --> 01:07:44,859
(And the highlight of alimango)

1675
01:07:45,099 --> 01:07:47,169
- My gosh. - The claw sure is...

1676
01:07:47,399 --> 01:07:49,998
- It's full of meat. - The claw sure is...

1677
01:07:49,999 --> 01:07:51,539
the real deal.

1678
01:07:55,509 --> 01:07:57,039
It looks so delicious.

1679
01:07:57,509 --> 01:07:58,638
It smells so good.

1680
01:07:58,639 --> 01:08:00,048
(You can only taste it in the Philippines,)

1681
01:08:00,049 --> 01:08:01,479
(which makes you become even more curious about the taste.)

1682
01:08:02,119 --> 01:08:03,319
Are you almost done?

1683
01:08:03,519 --> 01:08:04,549
- Yes. - Yes.

1684
01:08:04,749 --> 01:08:05,819
I'm so hungry I could die.

1685
01:08:07,519 --> 01:08:09,018
Please work a bit faster.

1686
01:08:09,019 --> 01:08:10,158
I got it.

1687
01:08:10,159 --> 01:08:12,488
(Jun Myun's hunger has reached its limits.)

1688
01:08:12,489 --> 01:08:13,689
I'm starting to feel rushed.

1689
01:08:13,859 --> 01:08:15,599
You need to stir-fry the rice too.

1690
01:08:16,699 --> 01:08:17,728
You're right.

1691
01:08:17,729 --> 01:08:19,099
(Rushing)

1692
01:08:21,199 --> 01:08:22,539
That's it. Done, right?

1693
01:08:22,769 --> 01:08:23,769
That's all.

1694
01:08:23,770 --> 01:08:25,639
(Eating)

1695
01:08:27,439 --> 01:08:28,468
Is it good?

1696
01:08:28,469 --> 01:08:31,039
(Dex tries it too.)

1697
01:08:32,709 --> 01:08:34,748
It's very sweet.

1698
01:08:34,749 --> 01:08:36,119
(Eating hurriedly before they get caught)

1699
01:08:36,279 --> 01:08:38,348
- It's very creamy. - Yes.

1700
01:08:38,349 --> 01:08:39,389
Right?

1701
01:08:40,049 --> 01:08:41,249
It's tasty.

1702
01:08:41,349 --> 01:08:43,188
- Hye Yoon, clean up. - Yes, sir.

1703
01:08:43,189 --> 01:08:44,458
Sir, take this.

1704
01:08:44,459 --> 01:08:45,928
(After the perfect crime, they pretend to rush.)

1705
01:08:45,929 --> 01:08:47,628
I'll get started now.

1706
01:08:47,629 --> 01:08:48,629
Okay.

1707
01:08:49,259 --> 01:08:51,229
Nice. I'll start, Hye Yoon.

1708
01:08:51,429 --> 01:08:52,469
Okay.

1709
01:08:55,499 --> 01:08:57,539
(Apply a generous amount of oil onto the wok.)

1710
01:08:58,099 --> 01:09:00,109
I'll make green onion oil first.

1711
01:09:01,039 --> 01:09:03,678
(Making green onion oil, the foundation of fried rice)

1712
01:09:03,679 --> 01:09:04,979
What will you season it with?

1713
01:09:05,649 --> 01:09:07,508
I'll use dark soy sauce...

1714
01:09:07,509 --> 01:09:09,318
- to season it. - Pass him dark soy sauce.

1715
01:09:09,319 --> 01:09:10,319
Okay.

1716
01:09:11,619 --> 01:09:12,788
Salt too.

1717
01:09:12,789 --> 01:09:13,789
Salt is here.

1718
01:09:15,489 --> 01:09:18,558
(Once enough green onion oil is released...)

1719
01:09:18,559 --> 01:09:20,159
Just a bit of carrots.

1720
01:09:20,529 --> 01:09:22,258
(A tiny bit)

1721
01:09:22,259 --> 01:09:24,929
- You should add more. - I don't really like carrots.

1722
01:09:25,329 --> 01:09:27,628
It's the owner's preference.

1723
01:09:27,629 --> 01:09:28,799
(Childish Dex's taste in food is ever so consistent.)

1724
01:09:29,439 --> 01:09:30,439
Eggs.

1725
01:09:30,440 --> 01:09:33,139
(Add the eggs that were beaten beforehand.)

1726
01:09:33,709 --> 01:09:36,708
(Pouring in firm rice cooked by Jung Ah)

1727
01:09:36,709 --> 01:09:37,739
Thank you.

1728
01:09:42,079 --> 01:09:46,749
(Coat it with savory golden color.)

1729
01:09:47,089 --> 01:09:49,489
You're such a great cook.

1730
01:09:50,219 --> 01:09:52,329
(Feeling shy)

1731
01:09:52,629 --> 01:09:53,728
I'm serious.

1732
01:09:53,729 --> 01:09:55,089
(To Hye Yoon, who can't cook, he's on a deity level.)

1733
01:09:55,659 --> 01:09:58,399
(When the rice is stir-fried nice and fluffy...)

1734
01:09:59,999 --> 01:10:02,838
(He pours soy sauce in the corner?)

1735
01:10:02,839 --> 01:10:04,298
They say soy sauce tastes better when it's slightly burned.

1736
01:10:04,299 --> 01:10:05,438
I heard it from somewhere.

1737
01:10:05,439 --> 01:10:06,769
(Stir-fry soy sauce as if burning it to add the smoky flavor.)

1738
01:10:08,269 --> 01:10:10,509
(You've improved a lot, Jin Young.)

1739
01:10:11,039 --> 01:10:13,879
(He pours stir-fried soy sauce onto the rice.)

1740
01:10:14,749 --> 01:10:19,149
(Stir-fry it once more so the smoky flavor can permeate.)

1741
01:10:19,249 --> 01:10:21,089
Prepare sesame oil.

1742
01:10:21,549 --> 01:10:23,489
Sprinkle one round of pepper.

1743
01:10:24,259 --> 01:10:25,259
- Me? - Yes.

1744
01:10:25,529 --> 01:10:26,859
Sesame... Pepper?

1745
01:10:27,729 --> 01:10:29,428
- Take it slow. - You want me to do it?

1746
01:10:29,429 --> 01:10:30,429
Yes, sprinkle the pepper.

1747
01:10:31,029 --> 01:10:32,029
That's right.

1748
01:10:32,769 --> 01:10:34,398
- Is this enough? - One more round.

1749
01:10:34,399 --> 01:10:35,598
(Adding a bold amount of pepper)

1750
01:10:35,599 --> 01:10:36,639
Is that enough?

1751
01:10:38,339 --> 01:10:39,869
Get sesame oil ready.

1752
01:10:40,039 --> 01:10:41,069
Here it is.

1753
01:10:42,239 --> 01:10:44,338
- Pour the oil. - Okay.

1754
01:10:44,339 --> 01:10:46,048
One big, bold round.

1755
01:10:46,049 --> 01:10:47,248
Like this.

1756
01:10:47,249 --> 01:10:48,409
That's it.

1757
01:10:49,979 --> 01:10:52,149
(Mission accomplished)

1758
01:10:52,249 --> 01:10:53,819
Get the crab meat ready.

1759
01:10:54,389 --> 01:10:55,589
- Crab meat? - Yes.

1760
01:10:56,019 --> 01:10:57,819
Crab meat. Didn't you add it in?

1761
01:10:58,559 --> 01:10:59,559
Crab meat?

1762
01:10:59,559 --> 01:11:00,559
(When did I add crab meat?)

1763
01:11:00,560 --> 01:11:01,729
Crab meat...

1764
01:11:02,259 --> 01:11:03,328
I didn't add it.

1765
01:11:03,329 --> 01:11:04,399
(Guess what's here.)

1766
01:11:06,129 --> 01:11:08,098
- Hye Yoon, what happened? - False...

1767
01:11:08,099 --> 01:11:09,299
Spreading false information.

1768
01:11:09,939 --> 01:11:11,299
I thought you already added it in.

1769
01:11:11,969 --> 01:11:13,038
- Here it is. - Pour it in.

1770
01:11:13,039 --> 01:11:14,069
(The assistant is all over the place.)

1771
01:11:15,439 --> 01:11:19,549
(The protagonist enters.)

1772
01:11:22,649 --> 01:11:23,878
I'll make it look as plentiful as possible.

1773
01:11:23,879 --> 01:11:27,289
(The harmony of savory fried rice and sweet alimango)

1774
01:11:29,389 --> 01:11:30,589
Bring a spoon.

1775
01:11:30,689 --> 01:11:31,719
Okay.

1776
01:11:32,429 --> 01:11:35,089
- It's for tasting, right? - Yes, and you'll be tasting it.

1777
01:11:35,259 --> 01:11:36,959
- Me? - Yes.

1778
01:11:37,229 --> 01:11:39,699
(The assistant's new mission: Tasting)

1779
01:11:40,599 --> 01:11:44,269
(How does alimango fried rice taste?)

1780
01:11:45,569 --> 01:11:47,309
(Blowing)

1781
01:11:48,009 --> 01:11:50,778
(Taking a bite carefully)

1782
01:11:50,779 --> 01:11:52,139
Let me know if it's bland.

1783
01:11:56,819 --> 01:11:58,878
It can't be too salty because we have the side dishes.

1784
01:11:58,879 --> 01:11:59,988
- Is that so? - Yes.

1785
01:11:59,989 --> 01:12:00,989
But...

1786
01:12:01,649 --> 01:12:03,518
(Chef Yum tries a bite too.)

1787
01:12:03,519 --> 01:12:05,118
- It's bland... It is, right? - It's bland.

1788
01:12:05,119 --> 01:12:06,158
It's definitely bland.

1789
01:12:06,159 --> 01:12:07,558
(Definitely bland)

1790
01:12:07,559 --> 01:12:09,228
It can't be too bland.

1791
01:12:09,229 --> 01:12:10,299
(She couldn't bring herself to say the truth.)

1792
01:12:10,859 --> 01:12:15,069
(He immediately adds extra salt.)

1793
01:12:16,469 --> 01:12:17,868
- Here. - Again?

1794
01:12:17,869 --> 01:12:19,168
Yes. Taste it.

1795
01:12:19,169 --> 01:12:20,209
(Tasting it the 2nd time)

1796
01:12:22,709 --> 01:12:26,749
(What about this time?)

1797
01:12:27,509 --> 01:12:30,279
Actually, I can't tell if it's seasoned enough or not.

1798
01:12:30,649 --> 01:12:32,248
I think it's just nice.

1799
01:12:32,249 --> 01:12:33,249
It's so bland.

1800
01:12:34,919 --> 01:12:36,858
(Hye Yoon should just stay as an assistant.)

1801
01:12:36,859 --> 01:12:37,918
It's bland.

1802
01:12:37,919 --> 01:12:42,059
(He adds more salt and stir-fries it one more time.)

1803
01:12:43,499 --> 01:12:48,198
(Tasting it the 3rd time)

1804
01:12:48,199 --> 01:12:49,239
(Nodding)

1805
01:12:50,069 --> 01:12:53,638
(Hye Yoon, who's lost her taste, tries again.)

1806
01:12:53,639 --> 01:12:54,908
(Nodding)

1807
01:12:54,909 --> 01:12:56,038
I think it's fine.

1808
01:12:56,039 --> 01:12:58,579
- I think it's good. - Yes, it's good.

1809
01:12:59,649 --> 01:13:00,909
This alone tastes good.

1810
01:13:01,079 --> 01:13:02,208
It's done.

1811
01:13:02,209 --> 01:13:03,478
(After ups and downs, alimango fried rice is done!)

1812
01:13:03,479 --> 01:13:04,479
Done.

1813
01:13:06,019 --> 01:13:08,388
(The golden fried rice...)

1814
01:13:08,389 --> 01:13:11,718
(goes onto a wooden plate, which looks very local.)

1815
01:13:11,719 --> 01:13:13,459
Put it down if it's heavy.

1816
01:13:13,759 --> 01:13:14,759
Okay.

1817
01:13:15,459 --> 01:13:16,828
There's quite a lot of rice.

1818
01:13:16,829 --> 01:13:19,769
(A generous amount fills up the plate.)

1819
01:13:21,129 --> 01:13:22,398
- Guys. - Yes?

1820
01:13:22,399 --> 01:13:23,539
- Yes? - How does it look?

1821
01:13:24,139 --> 01:13:26,838
- Doesn't it look delicious? - It looks so delicious.

1822
01:13:26,839 --> 01:13:28,168
(The second oldest prepared a dessert.)

1823
01:13:28,169 --> 01:13:29,709
Since we're in the Philippines, we should have some mangoes.

1824
01:13:30,239 --> 01:13:32,238
(The Philippines' representative fruit, mango,)

1825
01:13:32,239 --> 01:13:34,209
(which is very sweet and sour)

1826
01:13:34,579 --> 01:13:37,019
I can't wait to find out how it tastes.

1827
01:13:37,149 --> 01:13:38,149
Me too.

1828
01:13:39,419 --> 01:13:42,488
(Add Chef Yum's butter garlic sauce on top of it.)

1829
01:13:42,489 --> 01:13:44,259
I'll put the butter sauce on it.

1830
01:13:46,489 --> 01:13:47,528
It looks good.

1831
01:13:47,529 --> 01:13:51,659
(Soft, savory, and flavorful steamed butter garlic alimango)

1832
01:13:52,059 --> 01:13:54,828
- You went all out. - It's so good.

1833
01:13:54,829 --> 01:13:57,299
(Full of alimango's sweet taste, alimango fried rice)

1834
01:13:57,899 --> 01:13:59,769
And suddenly, we're in Korea.

1835
01:14:00,039 --> 01:14:01,238
It smells incredible.

1836
01:14:01,239 --> 01:14:03,679
(Refreshing and spicy beef radish soup)

1837
01:14:03,939 --> 01:14:05,748
- You can eat just with this. - That's right.

1838
01:14:05,749 --> 01:14:10,119
(And kimchi, which is a must for a Korean meal)

1839
01:14:13,149 --> 01:14:14,348
It looks legit.

1840
01:14:14,349 --> 01:14:15,718
(The siblings' fusion meal...)

1841
01:14:15,719 --> 01:14:17,089
(of Korean cuisine and the Filipino cuisine)

1842
01:14:17,119 --> 01:14:18,988
- Thank you for the meal. - Thank you for the meal.

1843
01:14:18,989 --> 01:14:20,459
Thank you for the meal.

1844
01:14:22,229 --> 01:14:23,229
(Glancing)

1845
01:14:23,230 --> 01:14:24,459
Would you like some fried rice?

1846
01:14:25,329 --> 01:14:28,069
(Hye Yoon distributes alimango fried rice.)

1847
01:14:28,229 --> 01:14:30,739
(She serves Jung Ah first, the oldest.)

1848
01:14:30,969 --> 01:14:31,969
(She distributes the fried rice strictly following the age order.)

1849
01:14:31,970 --> 01:14:33,069
Thank you.

1850
01:14:34,369 --> 01:14:36,438
I'd like 2 servings that look like 1.

1851
01:14:36,439 --> 01:14:38,709
- Two servings that look like one? - Is it the other way round?

1852
01:14:38,809 --> 01:14:39,809
If I press it like this...

1853
01:14:39,810 --> 01:14:42,078
(I scooped 2 servings and pressed it to make it look like 1.)

1854
01:14:42,079 --> 01:14:43,748
- How is it? - Hye Yoon, take yours.

1855
01:14:43,749 --> 01:14:45,179
I can scoop for myself.

1856
01:14:45,279 --> 01:14:46,619
No, I'm the youngest.

1857
01:14:46,919 --> 01:14:48,749
- Thank you. - It's Confucianism.

1858
01:14:49,419 --> 01:14:51,789
(Heartwarming)

1859
01:14:52,589 --> 01:14:54,888
(Scooping a lot for Dex since he worked hard making it)

1860
01:14:54,889 --> 01:14:55,929
Thank you.

1861
01:14:57,659 --> 01:14:59,629
(Lastly, Hye Yoon scoops the rice for herself.)

1862
01:15:00,199 --> 01:15:02,839
(They start their dinner in earnest.)

1863
01:15:05,939 --> 01:15:10,039
(How does Dex's alimango fried rice taste?)

1864
01:15:11,379 --> 01:15:13,449
(Glancing)

1865
01:15:13,749 --> 01:15:15,578
It tastes a bit bland, but...

1866
01:15:15,579 --> 01:15:17,018
- No, it's nice. - It's not bland.

1867
01:15:17,019 --> 01:15:18,119
- Really? - It's just nice.

1868
01:15:19,319 --> 01:15:21,488
It tastes like what they sell in restaurants.

1869
01:15:21,489 --> 01:15:22,558
- Go ahead. - Yes.

1870
01:15:22,559 --> 01:15:24,819
- If we had more crab meat... - Exactly.

1871
01:15:26,029 --> 01:15:28,089
It tastes like what they sell. You did a great job.

1872
01:15:28,729 --> 01:15:30,229
It's so good.

1873
01:15:30,629 --> 01:15:31,859
He's good.

1874
01:15:33,899 --> 01:15:35,398
This is so good.

1875
01:15:35,399 --> 01:15:37,169
- It's well-cooked. - It's so good.

1876
01:15:38,469 --> 01:15:40,709
(At their compliments, Dex starts eating in relief.)

1877
01:15:42,839 --> 01:15:45,779
(Dex successfully debuts as an alimango chef.)

1878
01:15:46,579 --> 01:15:49,979
(Hye Yoon, who assisted him well, takes a bite too.)

1879
01:15:50,119 --> 01:15:51,618
It's seasoned just right.

1880
01:15:51,619 --> 01:15:52,988
(The Generous Chef says the alimango fried rice is seasoned perfectly.)

1881
01:15:52,989 --> 01:15:54,248
- You don't need more or less. - Really?

1882
01:15:54,249 --> 01:15:56,519
- It's really good. - It's seasoned just right.

1883
01:15:57,389 --> 01:15:58,959
Gosh, I love geotjeori.

1884
01:15:59,729 --> 01:16:03,798
(Freshly made kimchi is Dex's favorite.)

1885
01:16:03,799 --> 01:16:04,859
The geotjeori's good, right?

1886
01:16:06,599 --> 01:16:08,369
I'm tasting fermented seafood. What is it?

1887
01:16:09,539 --> 01:16:10,539
Fermented seafood.

1888
01:16:11,039 --> 01:16:12,139
- It's fermented shrimp. - It's fermented shrimp.

1889
01:16:13,109 --> 01:16:14,269
There's fermented shrimp...

1890
01:16:15,039 --> 01:16:16,739
- And anchovy fish sauce. - and anchovy fish sauce in it.

1891
01:16:18,079 --> 01:16:21,349
(No wonder it's good.)

1892
01:16:21,509 --> 01:16:22,849
The kimchi is so good.

1893
01:16:22,949 --> 01:16:24,018
- Is it? - It has a clean taste.

1894
01:16:24,019 --> 01:16:25,019
When it ferments a little...

1895
01:16:25,949 --> 01:16:28,149
(The kimchi master is proud.)

1896
01:16:28,489 --> 01:16:30,559
(The beef radish soup that Jun Myun made following Jung Ah's recipe)

1897
01:16:30,859 --> 01:16:32,159
It's spicy and delicious.

1898
01:16:34,489 --> 01:16:36,359
(She takes a bite of the alimango fried rice...)

1899
01:16:37,159 --> 01:16:39,829
(and a spoonful of spicy beef radish soup.)

1900
01:16:40,499 --> 01:16:42,499
(Hye Yoon can't stop eating.)

1901
01:16:42,739 --> 01:16:44,138
I didn't think we'd get to eat Korean food here.

1902
01:16:44,139 --> 01:16:45,939
All of a sudden, it's like we're in Korea.

1903
01:16:46,439 --> 01:16:48,869
(Their first dinner in the Philippines...)

1904
01:16:50,509 --> 01:16:52,679
(doesn't feel unfamiliar at all.)

1905
01:16:52,909 --> 01:16:55,349
These precious crabs. They were so hard to catch.

1906
01:16:55,509 --> 01:16:58,119
I want to taste how good they are.

1907
01:16:58,449 --> 01:17:00,349
Let me do it.

1908
01:17:00,449 --> 01:17:02,389
(Dex prepares the claw so it's easier to eat.)

1909
01:17:03,019 --> 01:17:04,319
Be careful, you'll hurt your hands.

1910
01:17:05,619 --> 01:17:06,758
(Crack)

1911
01:17:06,759 --> 01:17:08,589
I do this and...

1912
01:17:08,829 --> 01:17:09,899
And then you use the scissors?

1913
01:17:10,929 --> 01:17:14,968
Yes. When I split this, we'll see the gem.

1914
01:17:14,969 --> 01:17:16,299
(When he removes the shell with scissors,)

1915
01:17:16,639 --> 01:17:20,068
(the juicy flesh is revealed.)

1916
01:17:20,069 --> 01:17:21,909
Here, Jung Ah. Have this.

1917
01:17:22,909 --> 01:17:24,478
- It's clean, right? - Since you're giving it to me,

1918
01:17:24,479 --> 01:17:25,479
I should eat it.

1919
01:17:25,480 --> 01:17:26,609
(The first claw goes to the eldest sister.)

1920
01:17:27,109 --> 01:17:28,948
(The second claw...)

1921
01:17:28,949 --> 01:17:30,519
- Here, Jun Myun. - Thank you.

1922
01:17:32,349 --> 01:17:33,588
(How does the alimango taste?)

1923
01:17:33,589 --> 01:17:34,819
(Yum)

1924
01:17:36,289 --> 01:17:38,119
(The sweet flavor of the alimango spreads in her mouth.)

1925
01:17:42,429 --> 01:17:46,029
(Jun Myun loves it.)

1926
01:17:46,869 --> 01:17:49,029
(Hye Yoon, the youngest sister, goes for the crab's top shell.)

1927
01:17:49,669 --> 01:17:51,939
(Scraping it clean)

1928
01:17:54,009 --> 01:17:55,368
(It's good.)

1929
01:17:55,369 --> 01:17:56,439
You...

1930
01:17:57,009 --> 01:17:59,909
You put this sauce on the flesh.

1931
01:18:01,009 --> 01:18:02,649
Spread it all over like this.

1932
01:18:04,779 --> 01:18:08,149
(Crunch)

1933
01:18:11,259 --> 01:18:14,128
Isn't this crab creamier?

1934
01:18:14,129 --> 01:18:15,129
Yes, it is.

1935
01:18:15,529 --> 01:18:16,929
It has a richer flavor too.

1936
01:18:17,129 --> 01:18:19,198
- The flavor, right? - Yes.

1937
01:18:19,199 --> 01:18:20,199
(It's creamier and has a richer flavor than the Korean blue crab.)

1938
01:18:20,529 --> 01:18:22,399
And it's sweet. It's very sweet.

1939
01:18:22,569 --> 01:18:24,239
The flavor feels a bit aloof.

1940
01:18:25,599 --> 01:18:27,109
What do you mean?

1941
01:18:28,069 --> 01:18:29,308
The crab is aloof?

1942
01:18:29,309 --> 01:18:30,609
(He's never heard the flavor of a crab be described as aloof.)

1943
01:18:30,709 --> 01:18:33,509
The Korean blue crab has a more umami flavor,

1944
01:18:34,349 --> 01:18:37,978
while this tastes sweet at first and clean at the end.

1945
01:18:37,979 --> 01:18:40,488
So the flavor is aloof.

1946
01:18:40,489 --> 01:18:42,089
(Aloof: When a food has a clean after taste)

1947
01:18:42,349 --> 01:18:45,489
(Jun Myun ate a lot of food in an aloof manner.)

1948
01:18:45,959 --> 01:18:48,459
(That's cute.)

1949
01:18:48,929 --> 01:18:50,629
(Just then, as the four siblings were lost in the alimango feast...)

1950
01:18:54,869 --> 01:18:56,069
I'm scared.

1951
01:18:56,599 --> 01:18:57,869
(Squeak)

1952
01:18:58,369 --> 01:19:00,339
(The strange sound won't stop.)

1953
01:19:01,109 --> 01:19:02,169
What is that?

1954
01:19:02,569 --> 01:19:04,509
(Even the production crew is starting to murmur at the sound.)

1955
01:19:04,979 --> 01:19:06,149
(Squeak)

1956
01:19:06,479 --> 01:19:08,749
(They look up at where the sound is coming from,)

1957
01:19:08,909 --> 01:19:11,979
(but there's nothing there.)

1958
01:19:14,349 --> 01:19:16,519
(So creepy)

1959
01:19:16,789 --> 01:19:17,859
What's that sound?

1960
01:19:19,659 --> 01:19:21,729
This is my first time hearing it, but that's the sound a lizard makes.

1961
01:19:22,189 --> 01:19:23,899
- That's a lizard? - Yes.

1962
01:19:24,199 --> 01:19:25,429
- Where is it? - You're lying.

1963
01:19:25,859 --> 01:19:26,898
(Squeak)

1964
01:19:26,899 --> 01:19:28,168
- It's true. - You're lying.

1965
01:19:28,169 --> 01:19:29,199
I'm serious.

1966
01:19:30,769 --> 01:19:31,799
Seriously?

1967
01:19:32,639 --> 01:19:34,368
Are you pranking me?

1968
01:19:34,369 --> 01:19:35,369
Gosh.

1969
01:19:35,370 --> 01:19:38,179
I asked because I heard it earlier.

1970
01:19:39,139 --> 01:19:40,248
(Squeaking)

1971
01:19:40,249 --> 01:19:42,549
(It is indeed the sound a lizard makes.)

1972
01:19:42,849 --> 01:19:45,148
(This is a male lizard's mating call.)

1973
01:19:45,149 --> 01:19:46,249
Really?

1974
01:19:46,619 --> 01:19:47,619
That's great.

1975
01:19:49,019 --> 01:19:50,488
It's as if the lizard is wearing a mic.

1976
01:19:50,489 --> 01:19:52,458
- It's pretty. With floral prints. - That's a bit scary-looking.

1977
01:19:52,459 --> 01:19:53,628
(I failed to find a mate yet again!)

1978
01:19:53,629 --> 01:19:54,829
We'll have to sleep with the windows closed.

1979
01:19:55,559 --> 01:19:57,028
Have some mangoes.

1980
01:19:57,029 --> 01:19:58,699
Cutting them wasn't easy.

1981
01:19:59,299 --> 01:20:00,428
Since we're in the Philippines.

1982
01:20:00,429 --> 01:20:02,069
Since we're in the Philippines, we should have mangoes.

1983
01:20:02,699 --> 01:20:04,099
I love mangoes.

1984
01:20:05,699 --> 01:20:07,639
(Taking a bite)

1985
01:20:07,939 --> 01:20:08,939
(Yum)

1986
01:20:09,539 --> 01:20:11,939
(Dex, the siblings' picky eater)

1987
01:20:12,709 --> 01:20:16,519
(And the youngest, Hye Yoon...)

1988
01:20:16,549 --> 01:20:17,549
It's so good.

1989
01:20:17,550 --> 01:20:19,689
It's really good.

1990
01:20:20,319 --> 01:20:25,788
(They all take bites of the mangoes while holding them like harmonicas.)

1991
01:20:25,789 --> 01:20:26,928
I love mangoes.

1992
01:20:26,929 --> 01:20:28,389
(As for Jun Myun, who prepared the mangoes herself)

1993
01:20:29,029 --> 01:20:30,059
(Her 1st mango slice)

1994
01:20:30,559 --> 01:20:31,559
(Her 2nd mango slice)

1995
01:20:32,029 --> 01:20:33,029
(Her 3rd mango slice)

1996
01:20:33,529 --> 01:20:36,969
(She had three mango slices in a row.)

1997
01:20:37,199 --> 01:20:38,699
(Amazed)

1998
01:20:38,899 --> 01:20:41,469
I had three slices by myself. I'll stop now.

1999
01:20:43,909 --> 01:20:45,109
Have some more.

2000
01:20:45,409 --> 01:20:46,609
No, I had enough.

2001
01:20:51,349 --> 01:20:52,748
I thought you were going to stop eating.

2002
01:20:52,749 --> 01:20:53,849
No, I lied.

2003
01:20:56,519 --> 01:20:58,018
(Her lie was exposed just 15 seconds later.)

2004
01:20:58,019 --> 01:20:59,259
I lied.

2005
01:20:59,589 --> 01:21:01,258
- She lied. - I had to lie.

2006
01:21:01,259 --> 01:21:02,429
(Mango Park, the liar, is eating her 4th slice.)

2007
01:21:03,059 --> 01:21:04,559
You really love mangoes.

2008
01:21:05,259 --> 01:21:06,629
Mango isn't the only thing she loves.

2009
01:21:10,299 --> 01:21:12,698
Jung Ah! How could you?

2010
01:21:12,699 --> 01:21:14,968
We're in the Philippines.

2011
01:21:14,969 --> 01:21:18,178
We should be getting along, if anything.

2012
01:21:18,179 --> 01:21:19,549
(Absolutely hilarious)

2013
01:21:20,679 --> 01:21:22,549
Mangoes are ridiculously cheap here.

2014
01:21:22,809 --> 01:21:24,119
They were the cheapest, right?

2015
01:21:24,879 --> 01:21:27,718
They were 150 pesos per kilo.

2016
01:21:27,719 --> 01:21:28,949
How much is that?

2017
01:21:29,319 --> 01:21:30,688
I think 100 pesos are equivalent to 2.5 dollars.

2018
01:21:30,689 --> 01:21:32,018
- Gosh. - Then that's...

2019
01:21:32,019 --> 01:21:33,658
- That's 2.5 dollars for 6 mangoes. - That's so...

2020
01:21:33,659 --> 01:21:35,388
- That's so cheap. - That's very cheap.

2021
01:21:35,389 --> 01:21:36,459
(These local mangoes taste great for how cheap they are.)

2022
01:21:36,559 --> 01:21:38,658
- In Korea, mangoes are... - They're very expensive.

2023
01:21:38,659 --> 01:21:39,799
They're expensive in Korea.

2024
01:21:40,199 --> 01:21:42,728
- I especially love apple mangoes. - Apple mangoes are really good.

2025
01:21:42,729 --> 01:21:45,038
It costs 25 dollars to buy 1 apple mango.

2026
01:21:45,039 --> 01:21:46,039
To buy one?

2027
01:21:47,169 --> 01:21:49,938
- For one apple mango? - Yes, so it's my dream to become...

2028
01:21:49,939 --> 01:21:52,339
someone who doesn't suck on the pit of an apple mango.

2029
01:21:53,279 --> 01:21:55,779
(A truly ambitious dream)

2030
01:21:55,879 --> 01:21:58,219
(Laughing)

2031
01:21:58,279 --> 01:21:59,589
What are we going to do with those?

2032
01:22:00,289 --> 01:22:02,389
- The pits? I'll suck on them. - The pits.

2033
01:22:02,689 --> 01:22:03,819
I'm not that person yet.

2034
01:22:04,519 --> 01:22:07,459
(Of course Mango Park has a plan.)

2035
01:22:07,659 --> 01:22:09,899
You'll have to find a blind spot with no cameras.

2036
01:22:09,999 --> 01:22:11,699
Or take them into the bathroom.

2037
01:22:11,959 --> 01:22:13,728
I feel pathetic for not even eating the pit.

2038
01:22:13,729 --> 01:22:16,569
Sucking on the pit is the best part.

2039
01:22:16,939 --> 01:22:18,569
You know how to enjoy your food.

2040
01:22:19,499 --> 01:22:21,769
(Mango Park will continue to shine.)

2041
01:22:21,869 --> 01:22:24,939
How are we going to make up for all the money we spent today?

2042
01:22:25,379 --> 01:22:27,348
We have to cover all the money, but how?

2043
01:22:27,349 --> 01:22:28,349
(They're starting to worry about tomorrow's groceries.)

2044
01:22:28,350 --> 01:22:31,278
Even if you don't have money,

2045
01:22:31,279 --> 01:22:34,089
if you earn coins,

2046
01:22:34,289 --> 01:22:36,918
you can use them to get our "local market pass."

2047
01:22:36,919 --> 01:22:38,359
It comes with an unlimited budget.

2048
01:22:39,419 --> 01:22:40,659
The coins are all you need.

2049
01:22:41,589 --> 01:22:42,829
You get food too.

2050
01:22:43,459 --> 01:22:45,159
(They can earn coins to get items...)

2051
01:22:45,729 --> 01:22:47,529
(from the drawing machine, which they can add to their itinerary.)

2052
01:22:47,699 --> 01:22:50,399
(They can even eat out without any money!)

2053
01:22:51,139 --> 01:22:54,039
(The siblings are on a vacation with the all-purpose coins!)

2054
01:22:54,309 --> 01:22:55,669
How are we supposed to earn the coins?

2055
01:22:56,109 --> 01:23:00,078
How were the games you played at the pre-production meeting?

2056
01:23:00,079 --> 01:23:02,879
- They were fun. - They were refreshing.

2057
01:23:03,019 --> 01:23:04,718
It was like "Family Entertainment Show" was brought back to life.

2058
01:23:04,719 --> 01:23:05,719
(It was like "Family Entertainment Show" was brought back to life.)

2059
01:23:07,319 --> 01:23:08,419
Like a family game show.

2060
01:23:08,819 --> 01:23:10,388
You can play a game...

2061
01:23:10,389 --> 01:23:11,889
- to win coins. - Let's do it.

2062
01:23:11,989 --> 01:23:13,089
What is the game?

2063
01:23:14,529 --> 01:23:17,699
(Will the siblings be able to earn as many coins as they want?)

2064
01:23:20,399 --> 01:23:22,628
All right. Day One is over as of now.

2065
01:23:22,629 --> 01:23:24,138
We finished cooking too.

2066
01:23:24,139 --> 01:23:25,438
(Day 1 of their vacation abroad is over.)

2067
01:23:25,439 --> 01:23:27,538
I think there are new items here.

2068
01:23:27,539 --> 01:23:30,278
"Drinking Mohitos in Bohol." This is the first time I'm seeing that one.

2069
01:23:30,279 --> 01:23:31,579
"At-Home Cafe Unlocked?"

2070
01:23:32,009 --> 01:23:33,009
An at-home cafe?

2071
01:23:33,010 --> 01:23:34,678
- Those are new. - They've been added, right?

2072
01:23:34,679 --> 01:23:36,948
Things like "Korean Delivery Pass."

2073
01:23:36,949 --> 01:23:38,649
These are actually...

2074
01:23:38,749 --> 01:23:39,848
- We can order delivery. - That's awesome.

2075
01:23:39,849 --> 01:23:40,849
- These are great. - They're awesome.

2076
01:23:40,850 --> 01:23:42,689
- We don't have to cook. - We can pass on cooking dinner.

2077
01:23:42,789 --> 01:23:44,818
I think they keep adding new ones to replace the ones we use.

2078
01:23:44,819 --> 01:23:45,819
I think so too.

2079
01:23:46,019 --> 01:23:50,028
So the more coins you earn through these games,

2080
01:23:50,029 --> 01:23:53,698
the more lavish your vacation would be.

2081
01:23:53,699 --> 01:23:55,769
- I see. - Got it.

2082
01:23:55,929 --> 01:23:57,739
Let's get going. What game are we playing?

2083
01:23:58,999 --> 01:24:00,838
(There's a crazed look in Jung Ah's eyes.)

2084
01:24:00,839 --> 01:24:02,909
The game you'll be playing today...

2085
01:24:03,509 --> 01:24:05,539
- is a revenge match. - Okay.

2086
01:24:05,779 --> 01:24:06,849
- A revenge? - Yes.

2087
01:24:07,279 --> 01:24:09,818
To be honest, we were weak-hearted,

2088
01:24:09,819 --> 01:24:14,248
